bug.short_desc: Resume from Suspend to RAM on second time broken on Lenovo Yoga 900 13ISK
bug.cf_doc_type: If docs needed, set a value

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 1265352 dmesg before suspend 1
Description of problem: Suspend to RAM and resume works fine for the first time, with the power indicator blinking to indicate system is on sleep. Next time laptop goes into suspend to RAM due to inactivity, it does not resume. The power indicator remains on, does not blink. Powercycle required to boot into the system again.
Version-Release number of selected component (if applicable): kernel-4.9.14-200.fc25.x86_64
How reproducible: Always. The behaviour can also be reproduced using 'echo mem > /sys/power/state'.
Steps to Reproduce: 1. dmesg > dmesg_before1; echo mem > /sys/power/state; dmesg > dmesg_after1 2. Wake up the system by pressing power button slightly or pressing keys on keyboard 3. dmesg > dmesg_before2; echo mem > /sys/power/state; dmesg > dmesg_after2
Actual results: Pressing power button or keys/touchpad doesn't bring the system back. Hard reboot/power cycling required. No dmesg_after2 file generated from step 3.
Expected results: Laptop resumes correctly.
Additional info: I remember that multiple s2ram & resume used to work in initial kernels of F25 (don't remember exactly, but 4.5 or 4.6); so this is a regression. Also attaching the dmesg_before1, dmesg_after1 and dmesg_before1. Hardware: Lenovo Yoga 900 13 ISK BIOS version: C6CN39WW Let me know if you need any input or steps required if I can help with debugging further.

*********** MASS BUG UPDATE **************
We apologize for the inconvenience. There is a large number of bugs to go through and several of them have gone stale. Due to this, we are doing a mass bug update across all of the Fedora 25 kernel bugs.
Fedora 25 has now been rebased to 4.10.9-200.fc25. Please test this kernel update (or newer) and let us know if you issue has been resolved or if it is still present with the newer kernel.
If you have moved on to Fedora 26, and are still experiencing this issue, please change the version to Fedora 26.
If you experience different issues, please open a new bug report for those.
So yes, I've been running kernel-4.10.8-200.fc25.x86_64 since a few days and it seems multiple suspend-resume resume works reliably. Shall close this bug.
